\pard\plain \sa160\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs48\b1 Promising the Impossible}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\i1 Genesis 17:1\endash 18:15}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs32 Setting the Stage}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs22\b1 Theme.}{\f0\fs24  While it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s easy to pay lip service to the idea that God is all powerful, it\u8217\'92s much more difficult to consistently live out our faith in ways that recognize God\u8217\'92s unlimited ability\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 His omnipotence. Like other characteristics attributed to God, omnipotence can be a difficult idea to wrap our heads around. The story of Abram and Sarai shows that even the heroes of faith sometimes found it difficult to acknowledge God\u8217\'92s power in their lives.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 In Genesis 17 and 18, Sarai and Abram struggled to keep their composure when God delivered the seemingly ridiculous news that Sarai\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a 90-year-old woman who had been barren her whole life\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 would give birth to a son. In response to Sarai\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s laughter of disbelief, God raised the issue of His omnipotence, asking, \u8220\'93Is anything too difficult for Yahweh?\u8221\'94 (Gen 18:14). The story goes on to show that \u8220\'93with God all things are possible\u8221\'94 (Matt 19:22), even when we have trouble believing it. God eventually made Sarai a mother, demonstrating His ability to bring life from a previously lifeless womb\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and He did so despite the couple\u8217\'92s doubts.}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs22\b1 Literary Context.}{\f0\fs24  As we\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve seen, God repeated His promise to Abram several times throughout his life. Each time, God made the promise more specific. He first promised Abram that he would become a \u8220\'93great nation\u8221\'94 (Gen 12:1\endash 3) and identified the land that He would give to Abram\u8217\'92s offspring (Gen 12:7). Later, He revealed that Abram\u8217\'92s descendants would be as numerous as the dust of the earth (Gen 13:14\endash 17). Even later, He made it known that the heir to the promise would be Abram\u8217\'92s own son (Gen 15:4) and identified the specific location of the promised land (Gen 15:18\endash 21).}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 In Genesis 17:1\endash 27, God again reaffirmed His promise to Abram. While most of this promise resembled earlier versions, a few things were new. God stated that kings would be included among Abram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s descendants (Gen 17:6, 16) and emphasized that a son birthed by Sarai would inherit the covenant (Gen 17:19). Here, God also changed the names of Abram and Sarai to Abraham and Sarah and established circumcision as the sign of the covenant.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 In the chapter that follows, three men visit Abraham on their way to Sodom (Gen 18:1\endash 15). While we are told that \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yahweh appeared to [Abraham]\u8221\'94 (Gen 18:1), the chapter does not identify the three men or provide details about their interaction with Abraham (they appear in Gen 18:2). Rather, it focuses on Abraham\u8217\'92s hospitality; he invited the men to rest and provided a feast for them (Gen 18:3\endash 8). These men are typically understood as messengers from God or a representation of God Himself (see \u8220\'93Beyond the Bible\u8221\'94).}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs22\b1 Historical & Cultural Background.}{\f0\fs24  The story of Gen 18 illustrates the significance of hospitality in the ancient Near East. The Babylonian Talmud says, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Greater value attaches to hospitality \u8230\'85 than receiving the presence of God.\u8221\'94 Hosts were responsible for protecting their guests as well as providing water (so visitors could wash their feet) and a meal (see Gen 24:32; 43:24; Judg 19:21). They were also expected to care for their guests\u8217\'92 animals (see Gen 24:31\endash 32; 43:24).}
