\row}\pard
\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 The social and cultural significance of hospitality is also evident in the Psalms, which sometimes portray God as a host. Psalm 23 describes the provision and protection that comes with being a guest in the house of Yahweh; it tells how God satisfies the psalmist\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s hunger by setting a \u8220\'93table\u8221\'94 before him and provides him with sanctuary by doing so \u8220\'93in the presence of [his] oppressors\u8221\'94 (Psa 23:5\endash 6). Psalm 36:8 likewise describes the refreshment that comes to those who take refuge in God\u8217\'92s house.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 The Gospel writers also used the role of host in their portrayal of Jesus and His ministry. Jesus practiced hospitality by providing food for the crowds that had been following Him (Mark 8:1\endash 9). He also served as a host when washing His disciples\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92 feet; earlier, He had criticized a Pharisee for not providing Him with this service (John 13:3\endash 5; see Luke 7:44\endash 47). Understanding ancient Near Eastern hospitality helps us better understand not only Abraham\u8217\'92s story, but other biblical passages as well.}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs32 A Closer Look}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Genesis 17 opens by telling us \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Abram was ninety-nine years old\u8221\'94 when Yahweh appeared to him again (Gen 17:1). Thirteen years had passed since the events of Gen 15\endash 16 (see Gen 16:16), yet the narrative doesn\u8217\'92t focus on this fact. Instead, it simply presents God\u8217\'92s reiteration of the promise. This shows that the relationship between the events of Gen 16 and 17 is more important than }{\f0\fs24\i1 when}{\f0\fs24  the events of each chapter occurred. Previously, Sarai had tried to bring about the fulfillment of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s promise by providing Abram with an heir through Hagar. Here, as we\u8217\'92ll see, God affirmed that Sarai herself would bear a son. This particular arrangement of events emphasizes the themes of promise and faith in Abram and Sarai\u8217\'92s life.}
