\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 The chapter begins with God once more interacting directly with Abram, identifying Himself as \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93El-Shaddai\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93God Almighty\u8221\'94 (Gen 17:1). In His previous encounters with Abram, God had required very little from him (see Gen 12, 15). Here, God commanded that Abram \u8220\'93walk before me and be blameless,\u8221\'94 establishing Abram\u8217\'92s obedience as a condition of His blessing and covenant (Gen 17:1\endash 2).}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 God also restated the promise and reinstated the covenant\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a course of action required by the events of Gen 16. The time for fulfillment of the promise was drawing near. God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s reassurance to Abram in Gen 15 had focused on the promise of the land (see Chapter 4, \u8220\'93A Closer Look\u8221\'94). In this reinstatement of the covenant promise, God emphasized that Abram would be the \u8220\'93father of a multitude of nations\u8221\'94 (Gen 17:4\endash 5). God had already attempted to give Abram some sense of how numerous his descendants would be, comparing their number to the dust of the earth (Gen 13:16) and the stars of the sky (Gen 15:5). Here, He emphasized that Abram would father not only a \u8220\'93great nation,\u8221\'94 but a \u8220\'93multitude\u8221\'94 of them (Gen 17:4). To underscore this promise, God renamed him Abraham, connecting his new name to the promise that he would father this multitude (Gen 17:5). No longer would Abraham merely be a revered figure; he would become the ancestor to whom many people groups would trace their beginning.}
