\row}\pard
\pard\plain \fi360\sa160\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 God then introduced circumcision by commanding Abraham, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93you must keep my covenant, you and your offspring after you, throughout their generations\u8221\'94 (Gen 17:9). Previously, the covenant simply established that Canaan would belong to Abraham\u8217\'92s descendants (Gen 15:18\endash 21). Now, the covenant required obedience to God\u8217\'92s command that every male be circumcised. As \u8220\'93a sign of the covenant,\u8221\'94 circumcision functioned as a symbol\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 an external act of obedience that testified to an inward faith in God\u8217\'92s promise (Gen 17:11). The symbolism of circumcision had a lasting impact on biblical writers (see \u8220\'93Throughout the Bible\u8221\'94).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 After providing details on circumcision (Gen 17:11\endash 14), God renamed Sarai, calling her Sarah (both names mean \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93princess\u8221\'94; Gen 17:15). Then, God finally provided Abraham with the essential detail: The promised son would be born through Sarah (Gen 17:16). As if to emphasize the link between His promise to Abraham and His blessing of Sarah, God continued by stating that nations and kings would come through her (Gen 17:16). Stunned by this revelation, Abraham laughed, wondering how an elderly couple could have children (Gen 17:17). He then addressed God, begging Him to bless his son, Ishmael, instead (Gen 17:18). But God\u8217\'92s plan was set: Isaac would be the son of the promise (Gen 17:19, 21).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 After 24 years of waiting on God, Abraham finally received a concrete timeframe: Sarah would have a son within the year (Gen 17:21). With this final assurance in place, Abraham proceeded to circumcise every male in his household, as God commanded (Gen 17:23).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 In the scene that follows, Abraham offered hospitality to three divine messengers (Gen 18:1\endash 15), who repeated the promise that Sarah would have a son within the year (Gen 18:10). This episode focuses on Sarah\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s response to this prophecy: Upon overhearing their announcement, she laughed in disbelief. While Sarah\u8217\'92s reaction is understandable, given her age and lifelong inability to conceive, Yahweh chastised Sarah for her doubt (Gen 18:13). Sarah denied her reaction, likely out of surprise over the scolding and for having the visitor know her thoughts (Gen 18:15).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 As the story ends, the sense of immediacy in this selective presentation of events from Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s life becomes apparent (Gen 16\endash 18:15). Abram may have patiently waited on God during the 13 years between Gen 16 and 17. Perhaps he had assumed Ishmael would be his heir and that God had approved of their intervention via Hagar (implied by his reaction in Gen 17:18). Ultimately, however, these stories show that God seems to take delight in performing the impossible.}
\par\pard\plain \sa160\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f3\fs24\i1 Study Questions}
\par\pard\plain \tx360\li360\fi-360\sa160\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 1.\tab Reflect on a time when you felt God leading you toward something that you felt was impossible. How did you respond?}
\par\pard\plain \li360\sa160\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \tx360\li360\fi-360\sa160\sb180\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 2.\tab Consider the difference between obedience as a sign that you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re following God versus the means by which you fulfill your obligation to God. Which option makes your faith seem more secure?\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f4\fs24\b0\i0  Grigoni, M. R., Custis, M., Mangum, D., & Whitehead, M. M. (2012). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/csabraham?ref=Bible.Ge17.1-18.15&off=10&ctx=CHAPTER+5%0a~Promising+the+Impossible%0aGenes"}{\fldrslt\f5\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4 Abraham: Following God\loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8217\'92s Promise\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f4\fs24\b0\i0  (Ge 17:1\endash 18:15). Bellingham, WA: Lexham Press.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
